This document has commentary specific to businesses of the Marketplace phenotype. We view the typical business types as below:

4-Wall refers to businesses which have a physical real estate footprint / retail stores to serve customers. These stores are often referred to as “boxes” or “sites”. They incur certain OpEx, such as site rent costs, that are associated with having a physical footprint. They will often report financials by site, attributing revenue and costs that occur within the “4 walls” of the store and excluding corporate overhead costs
Within 4 Wall, healthcare businesses frequently can be broken down into:
DTC model (direct-to-consumer business with physical stores)
Reimbursement model (earns revenue through reimbursements from insurance companies)

A direct-to-consumer (DTC) business markets and sells its products directly to the end customer and bypasses any third-party retailers, wholesalers, or other middlemen. These kinds of businesses can also sometimes be called Business to Consumer or B2C businesses.
B2B companies sell products and services to other businesses, rather than directly to consumers
“B2B” and “Enterprise” are terms that are sometimes interchanged, but frequently “Enterprise” refers to companies selling products & services via big contracts to large enterprise corporations
A subset of B2B companies can be considered B2B2C, which means that even though the products/services are sold to a business, ultimately the end user of the services is the consumer
Examples of Enterprise / B2B businesses: Flatiron Health, Datadog, Docusign
A marketplace provides a platform to connect demand with supply, which results in financial transactions being executed between those who desire the product and those who are providing the product
The marketplace typically doesn’t own any of the supply or provide the product/service itself
Marketplaces typically make money by charging a small percentage of the total value of products/services transacted through their platform (also known as the “take rate”)
Identify the KPIs, financials and other data to be tracked for your business
Ensure that any systems / software necessary for data tracking are in place
For a deep dive into important metrics to track for your Business Type, see the “Key Metrics” section later in this document
Data to be tracked on a monthly basis for purposes of portfolio review for your business type can be found here:
For guidance on the setup of P&Ls and other fundamental financial reporting systems, see the “Financial Infrastructure Setup” section below
Prior to finalizing the company’s data infrastructure setup, we recommend that the management team consider:
The data that will be needed to calculate the important KPIs for your business (how it should be sourced and captured by your Business Intelligence system)
Whether cohorts or other segmenting will be useful in analyzing your business
We recommend setting up data infrastructure early on, so that not only will data exist and be usable for you to manage the business, but also so that it will be available for your next fundraise
Determine what financial metrics and sub-P&L’s will provide helpful visibility into your business operations (RH S&F team can assist if you believe the best practices shown above are not applicable)
Work with the Redesign Controller to set up Netsuite financial infrastructure accordingly

Upon OpCo launch (or as soon as possible), Redesign’s Controller (Olisa Ma) will help set your business up on Netsuite. Netsuite is an ERP, an enterprise resource planning tool, that will record your company’s financials
Development of quarterly and annual operating and financial plans
Tracking of KPIs to measure progress toward plan goals
Monthly management review of operating and financial performance, including variance versus plan
for a sample Annual Business Planning Framework
here are many forms of effective annual planning frameworks.  We suggest an OKR-based framework (OKR = objectives & key results) that includes the following basic elements:
that will be used to measure success in driving each objective
Generation of $X from new business opportunities
Improvement of customer retention by X%
Achievement of X% reduction in COGS
It’s useful to also include the measurable outcome (e.g., KPI target) that will show the strategy has been completed, and the strategy “owner”
Considerations when determining annual plan objectives
should be consistent with and reflect alignment among management on the company’s core business model

When identifying the quantitative goals that define success in advancing plan objectives, remember that the actuals of any metrics involved will need to be tracked on a regular (ideally monthly) basis in order to facilitate performance review

Take into account the investor perspective; remember that investors will look for proof points of the company’s ability to successfully execute its monetization model and other key elements of its plan during the fundraising process

Plans to pursue additional monetization channels should be carefully considered, taking into account the burden of GTM strategy, KPI & financial planning, and other implications, as well as the risk of diminishing focus on existing strategy and execution

Even if there is uncertainty around the upcoming year, it’s still essential to lay out a target financial case. If it seems daunting, begin by breaking your business’s performance down into the most basic building blocks -- for example, assumptions around speed of customer acquisition, pricing expectations, etc. -- in order to build up to annual and quarterly targets
The Financial Plan should not be created in a vacuum

Fundamentally, there should be strong communication between Finance personnel and Sales, Marketing and other functional teams in order to ensure that the company’s financial model and plan are closely aligned with the strategies functional teams will employ (e.g., bundling, discounting, or other strategies that characterize sales)

Create accountability and ownership of targets by generating organizational buy-in for the Financial Plan. We find it most effective when teams or individuals who are in charge of executing on aspects of the Plan are looped in to underwrite what they can sign up for. Examples of this could include:
Head of Marketing signs off on the Marketing Budget and what that budget can yield in terms of new customers or contracts for the business
Ops or Supply Chain leader signs off on product costs (COGS) and amount of labor required to support the revenue forecast
For 4 Wall businesses, Ops or Real Estate leader signs off on capex and rent budgets for the desired amount of office space
e recommend sharing the Quarterly and Annual goals internally across all relevant stakeholders and departments
Ensure that there is clear ownership of targets

Progress against quarterly and annual goals should be tracked regularly to ensure appropriate progress is being made, as well as identify root causes and response plans for underperformance / learnings when performance exceeds plan.  We recommend reviewing progress against the plan monthly (best practice), or quarterly at a minimum
When tracking below target, action plans should be developed to understand root causes and improvement
Identify the key KPIs for your business. This may include a mix of KPIs from the table(s) below, as well as others customized to your business specifically

Ensure KPIs can be calculated and captured for future reporting and business management. See “Data Infrastructure Setup” section earlier in this document. If they currently can’t be calculated, take steps to install that infrastructure -- it will pay dividends in the future!
Review the KPIs (Actuals vs Targets) regularly to ensure proper progress and allow for timely course corrections. See also the “Financial Planning & Tracking” section
Identify the right KPIs for your business early on

From the investor perspective: although each company is different, for each broad Business Type, at a high level investors will evaluate the company in a standard fashion, using common metrics to determine the company’s viability and attractiveness. The earlier you identify these and install the necessary infrastructure, the more history you will be able to pull at fundraising time
Create a primary dashboard of the key metrics for the company, and review Actuals compared to Targets regularly

Very early stage businesses should aim to include the Top 3-5 core metrics on this dashboard. Additional metrics (often the ones that are double-clicks from the top metrics) may form the basis for secondary dashboards
As you further scale (ie: Series A and beyond), aim to expand the primary dashboard to include your Top 10-15 metrics for increased visibility into the drivers of your business
We suggest identifying on this dashboard the internal team member who is responsible for hitting the metrics to reinforce ownership and accountability
Wherever possible, unit economics should be understood and updated frequently

Special Considerations for Insurance Reimbursement business models

In addition to strategic finance best practices & KPIs for your Business Type (e.g., 4 Wall, DTC, Enterprise, Marketplace), outlined in the following section, we list below certain considerations that all businesses that generating revenue from insurance reimbursements should take into account
1) Understand your revenue breakdown and customer breakdown BY PAYER CATEGORY
Tracking this breakdown can help you explain other trends happening in your business
If you are a national or multi-state business, having an understanding of this breakdown by geographic location can be useful as well. For example, Medicaid programs can differ significantly by state
Calculating Revenue-Per-Unit over time can be a good lagging indicator of shifts that are happening within payer category
Your Finance team member should pay detailed attention to payer assumptions when forecasting revenue and cash flow, including:
Revenue-Per-Unit (by geography and by payer category)
Volume of activity (by payer category) -- certain customers may use you more frequently than others
Receipt of cash (there will be a delay in insurance reimbursements from provision of the service, and the timing/success of reimbursement depends largely on the payer type)
Uncollectible revenue that never gets reimbursed by the insurer or copays that cannot be collected
3) Billing Success and Timing of Reimbursement are critical to a reimbursement-based business
Particularly as your business grows, it may become more important to have an employee or team focused on diligently collecting reimbursements

Stacked bar charts that show the percent of a certain month’s estimated revenue which was successfully collected within 30, 60, 90, and 120 days are useful, and expose when there is too high a percentage of the revenue which is uncollectible

NPS, or some type of satisfaction survey, can be conducted at any time for a company. NPS, in particular, has been favored because it’s a relatively simple survey to run, and you don’t need to have fancy software. It can be done with a Google form, SurveyMoney survey, etc.
Perhaps more important and actionable than the actual NPS score questions is including the open-ended question, “Why did you give us this score?”
detailing one startup’s process of automating their NPS program may contain useful insights
lays out other, alternative/unconventional techniques of measuring user satisfaction

Lesson Learned: Before launching any new products/services, ensure that the management team fully understands the unit economics of doing so. If helpful, leverage the RH S&F team for assistance.

Below are the KPIs we recommend for your Business Type, along with a benchmark to orient you as to what’s considered a “good” benchmark for each metric. While you may not be at the “best-in-class” benchmark today, the goal should be to work toward a path to get there that investors can underwrite.  We have also provided suggestions on the key metrics to focus on using yellow highlighting.
The number of customers who are using your service in a given time period
Each company must create their own definition of “Active” which is relevant to their platform
Cost to acquire an incremental new customer
[Total marketing spend in time period (not including sales & marketing salaried headcount)] / New customers attributable to that spend in time period
Depends on market size / competition; best when compared to LTV
Total dollar amount you expect to receive from a customer over the lifetime of their business with you
(LTV is typically calculated in monthly cohorts and compared to the relevant month’s CAC in the LTV/CAC ratio defined below)
Depends on market size / competition; best when compared to CAC
LTV/CAC represents the ROI of marketing spend to acquire customers
Measures the % of customers who continue to actively use your platform
User satisfaction metric that represents how likely users would be to recommend the product/service
Subtract the percentage of customers who are detractors from the percentage who are promoters -- resulting in a score between -100 and 100
The number of providers who are using your service in a given time period
Each company must create their own definition of “Active” which is relevant to their platform
Measures the % of providers who continue to actively use your platform
Measures how many customers an average provider can serve
# of Active Customers / # of Active Providers
The percentage of customer sessions that result in a transaction
The percent of products / services /  time offered by providers that is being purchased or used
Depends on the business, but generally should calculate the amount of product/service transacted, divided by the total amount of product/service offered
The length of time it takes from a product / service being offered to when it transacts
Depends on the business. An example: time between an eBay product listing and purchase
The number of transactions processed through your marketplace in a given time period
Average dollar amount spent per  transaction
Gross revenue in time period / Total transactions in time period
The total value of products / services being transacted
Total sales value of the products or services sold through your marketplace in a given time period
Measures the percentage of total sales value that your marketplace business keeps
Net Revenue is the dollar value that your business keeps as the “take rate” or commission

Marketplace businesses are unique because they bring together third parties on both the demand and supply side of the equation to transact with each other. This impacts the key metrics, because you will care about both sides in great detail. In this section, we have included insights that are applicable to the two-sided marketplace model.

Important: To understand the best practices, metrics, and sales funnel associated with the demand (consumer) side of the equation more completely, please also review the Direct-to-Consumer (DTC) phenotype playbook.
Here are 3 broad areas of non-financial KPIs to care about in two-sided marketplaces
How many customers are you acquiring? (signing up)
How many customers who sign up do you actually activate? (An example of activating a customer would be that they engage in a transaction)
Here, it will be important for your company to define its own measure of what an “Active” person is. An example could be if the customer had at least 1 session in a period.
Engagement is frequently measured in terms of # of customer sessions
Beyond a customer simply being Active, you may want to understand the level of activity/engagement across the customer population (ie: segment users)

For example, even if your definition of an Active person is that they book 1+ session in a period, you may want to monitor how many customers are booking 5+ sessions in a period. This means they are highly engaged and may be useful as a case study of “what is working well”
Retention measures the percent of activated customers who remain active users of your platform over time
How many providers are you acquiring? (signing up)
How many providers who sign up do you actually activate? (An example of activating a provider would be that they engage in a transaction or they offered a product/service through the platform)
For providers who are taking insurance:
How long it takes for a provider to get credentialed for reimbursement with insurance (for example, 30 days; 60 days; 90 days)
This impacts whether the provider is active on the platform, and the speed of supply-side acquisition
Engagement is frequently measured in terms of # of provider sessions
Retention measures the percent of activated providers who remain active on your platform over time
Again, it’s important for you to define your company’s measure of an “Active” provider. An example could be if the provider offered a product/service through the platform at least once in a period
(3) Balance metrics (measuring the effectiveness of the marketplace through interactions between customers and providers)

This is a good, basic starting point for understanding the balance of your marketplace. The ratio will give a high level sense of the average # of customers that one provider can serve, but for more insight we recommend going one level deeper, into either of the following Balance Metrics (session-to-transaction conversion; utilization)

What percent of customer sessions result in a transaction? This is a general measure of how effectively your marketplace is working, but often to understand trends in this conversion rate, you will need to dive into other metrics like provider availability, time-to-transact, etc. to understand root causes
For marketplaces powered by providers offering their time:  What % of providers’ time availability is being utilized?
For marketplaces powered by providers offering products/services:  what % of the products/services being offered are being purchased?

How long after a provider offers a product/service is it taking for a transaction to occur? (For example, with eBay listings, how long does it take to secure a buyer?) This is a measure of liquidity in your marketplace, and generally, the shorter the time to transact, the more value you are offering to both customers and providers
What is the total number of transactions powered by your platform?
What is the gross merchandise value (GMV) of those transactions?

There is no one-size-fits all in terms of when a company should hire its first Senior Finance employee.  For most companies, it is best to do so by the time of completing a Series B, with the exact timing depending on the factors below (the higher your business ranks in these factors, the sooner you should think of bringing on in-house Finance):
The complexity of modeling the business’s unit economics and financials
The overall volume and complexity of KPIs and other important metrics
The timing and potential complexity of future fundraising processes
Consider reaching out to RH S&F when you secure some initial customer data and proof points. They may be able to help model out your initial unit economics or recommend part-time CFO assistance
